WillPaginate
============

Sweet sweet pagination for your collections.


## Example usage: 

app/models/post.rb

  class Post < ActiveRecord::Base
    cattr_reader :per_page
    @@per_page = 50
  end

app/controller/posts_controller.rb

  def index
    @board = Board.find(params[:id])
    @entries = Post.paginate_by_board_id(@board.id, :page => params[:page])
  end

app/views/posts/index.rhtml

  <%= will_paginate %>


## Details

Post.paginate returns a PaginatedEntries instance that's a proxy to the original collection.
This instance knows about every aspect of pagination, so you don't have to pass additional
variables around. "will_paginate" view helper expects a PaginatedEntries instance and assumes
it is in @entries instance variable by default.

Couple of things to note:

  * Post.paginate => Post.find :all
  * Post.paginate_all_by_something => Post.find_all_by_something
  * Post.paginate_by_something     => Post.find_all_by_something (yep!)

Options for these finders are:

  * page          (default 1)
  * per_page      (default is read from the model, which is 30 if not overriden)
  * total entries: if not given, AR will count by itself
  * count:         takes place of "select" for count() statement
  * distinct:      also just for count() statement

Options for will_paginate helper method:

  * class:        CSS class name for the generated DIV (default "pagination")
  * prev_label:   default '&laquo; Previous',
  * next_label:   default 'Next &raquo;',
  * inner_offset: window around the current page, defaults to 4
  * outer_offset: window around beginning and end, defaults to 1


